node.text:
An exciting visitor swept along the coast of Wales recently, as photographer and marine biologist Jake Davies captured footage of the elusive angelshark (Squatina squatina) in a world-first for the UK coastline. Listed as Critically Endangered on the IUCN Red List of Threatened Species, the angelshark has been in decline for the last 50 years but this sighting of a juvenile in a novel location could help to inform conservation efforts to secure their future.

A member of the Chondrichthyes, a class of cartilaginous fish that contains sharks and rays, the angelshark has a rather exotic body plan. Much like a ray, it has winged fins and a flat body which it can submerge into the sand for a spot of ambush predating. Like some species of shark, it has impressive jaws which it can project outwards at speed to snap up passing fish before they’ve had a chance to even clock they’re in danger.
​
​​​Hit the image post via the link in our bio to read the full story 📖

Originally taken in black and white, a film of Benjamin, the last confirmed member of his species, who died on September 7, 1936, has been colorized and released to coincide with the 85th anniversary of the event, as well as National Threatened Species Day.

Small amounts of amethyst can be found in igneous, metamorphic, and sedimentary rocks all over the world. Amethyst is found in large quantities in the cavities of basalt flows in Brazil and Uruguay. Hundreds of pounds to several tons of amethyst crystals can be found in large cavities. 

It is formed inside basalts, which are igneous volcanic rocks formed by volcanic lava. These rocks act as vessels for minerals and water, forming the well-known white-purple crystal formation over time.

Happy #UnderwaterWednesday! Is it a crab? Is it a sponge? Actually, it’s a little bit of a lot of things. Decorator crabs are famous for adorning themselves with sedentary living things they find in their environment. Popular accessories include sponges, algae and tunicates. Their presence protects the crab either by camouflaging them or through aposematism, as their toxic properties and warning coloration keep hungry mouths away.

The deepsea lizardfish (Bathysaurus ferox) is found in tropical and subtropical seas across the world and is known to be one of the world's deepest living apex predators.

Adults grow to be over 70 cm long with a slender, cylindrical body and have a large mouth loaded with rows of sharp, needle-like teeth. These come in handy when hunting and killing fishes, mollusks, and even other lizardfish.

Deepsea lizardfish have adapted to the murky depths by evolving to have large livers that account for up to 20% of their total weight. This hefty organ serves as an energy reserve to keep them growing between feeding episodes which can creep on when hunting in the dark.

Video credit: NOAA

This is the blue sea squirt (Clavelina moluccensis), found in waters across the Indo-West Pacific. These sessile creatures are filter feeders that grow in clusters on dead corals and are particularly fond of overhangs.

They are light to medium blue in color and range in length from 0.5 to 2.5 cm. The zooids' tops have distinctive dark blue patches and spots that are constantly visible. They’re known to some as little bottles due to their resemblance to plastic bottles. Human trash, but make it fashion.

Image credit: Littlesam / Shutterstock.com

node.text:
Feast your eyes upon the Asian arowana (Scleropages formosus)! Popular among aquarists, the species is native to the blackwater rivers and wetlands in Southeast Asia. Unfortunately, they're endangered in the wild which is why they are the world’s most expensive aquarium fish.

Asian arowanas grow to almost a meter in length and have a carnivorous diet, feeding on shrimp, crickets, and feeder fish. They are known as “dragonfish” because of their resemblance to the legendary Chinese dragon and are thought to bring good luck and prosperity due to their red color and coin-like scales. 

Image credit: koifish / Shutterstock.

node.text:
Sad news. A new report from the IUCN (International Union for Conservation of Nature) has deemed the Komodo dragon an endangered species due to the increasing threats of climate change. The report states that the suitable habitats for the dragons will reduce by 30% in the next 45 years as a result of sea levels and global temperatures rising.
​ 
Image credits: Sergey Uryadnikov /  Gudkov Andrey / Shutterstock

Happy #MicrobeMonday! This is one of the largest single-celled organisms in the world (Bursaria truncatella) mercilessly swallowing a smaller organism (Paramecium) whole.

In terms of single-celled organisms, Bursaria truncatella is a real beast, and can be seen with the naked eye. Some of them reach up to 2mm long.

The Paramecium is taken inside Bursaria truncatella and wrapped in a membrane, where it will be covered in digestive enzymes and digested. Poor little cell.

Video credit: @jam_and_germs

This year over 7,000 entries were submitted to the Comedy Wildlife Photography Awards, and 42 finalists have been selected, with the prize winners to be announced in October.

“I was taking videos and trying slow motion videos. I was lucky to capture this amazing moment when one kingfisher just hurried and banged to another one. This was the first time I have seen something like that. It was lockdown time here, and looking like the friends are giving each other a hug after a big lockdown.” – Photographer Rahul Lakhmani
